                              ARTICLE 1 — DEFINITIONS
================================================================================

1.1  "License" means the terms and conditions set forth in this document in its
     entirety, including all articles, sections, and subsections.

1.2  "Licensor" means Faruk Alpay, the original author and copyright holder of
     the Software, and any successor or assignee of the Licensor's rights.

1.3  "Software" means the computer program known as "Spectral Packet Engine,"
     including but not limited to all source code files, object code, build
     scripts, configuration files, test suites, documentation, example files,
     data files, and any other materials included in the official repository
     located at the Licensor's designated hosting platform (currently GitHub),
     in whatever form they exist at any point in the version history.

1.4  "Source Code" means the preferred form of the Software for making
     modifications to it.  For compiled languages, this includes all source
     files necessary to generate the object code plus the scripts used to
     control compilation and installation.  For interpreted languages such as
     Python, the Source Code is the human-readable program text itself together
     with all associated configuration, build, test, and documentation files.

1.5  "Object Code" means any non-source form of a work, including but not
     limited to compiled code, bytecode, minified code, obfuscated code,
     serialized model weights derived from the Software's algorithms, and any
     other form that is not the preferred form for modification.

1.6  "Derivative Work" means any work that is based upon, incorporates,
     extends, modifies, translates, adapts, transforms, or is otherwise derived
     from the Software or any portion thereof, whether by modification of
     existing Source Code, addition of new Source Code that links to or imports
     from the Software, creation of a wrapper or interface layer around the
     Software, porting the Software to a different programming language or
     platform, or any other means by which a new work is created that contains
     or is based upon copyrightable elements of the Software.

     For the avoidance of doubt, the following are Derivative Works:

     (a) A fork of the Software's repository, whether or not any modifications
         have been made, if the fork is distributed to any third party;

     (b) A software library, framework, or application that imports, links to,
         calls, or otherwise depends upon any module, function, class, or
         interface of the Software at compile time or at runtime;

     (c) A software service, including but not limited to web applications, API
         endpoints, microservices, and cloud functions, that incorporates the
         Software or any Derivative Work as a component;

     (d) A machine learning model, surrogate model, or statistical model whose
         training process uses the Software's algorithms, basis functions,
         spectral decomposition routines, or any other computational method
         provided by the Software;

     (e) A reimplementation in any programming language of any algorithm,
         mathematical method, data structure, or computational technique that
         is original to the Software and not part of the prior art, where such
         reimplementation is substantially similar in structure, sequence, or
         organization to the Software's implementation.

     The following are NOT Derivative Works:

     (f) Independent works that merely receive output data (e.g., JSON files,
         CSV files, artifact bundles, numerical results) produced by the
         Software, provided that such works do not incorporate any Source Code
         or Object Code of the Software;

     (g) Works that communicate with the Software solely through a documented,
         stable, public protocol (such as MCP, HTTP, or SQL) without
         incorporating any of the Software's code, provided that the Software
         is used unmodified and is separately distributed under this License.

1.7  "Contribution" means any work of authorship, including but not limited to
     modifications, additions, deletions, bug fixes, feature implementations,
     documentation changes, test additions, and performance improvements, that
     is intentionally submitted to the Licensor for inclusion in the Software.
     A Contribution is "submitted" when it is sent to the Licensor or the
     Licensor's designated repository in any form, including but not limited to
     pull requests, merge requests, patches, emails, or issue comments that
     include code.

1.8  "Contributor" means the Licensor and any natural or legal person that has
     submitted a Contribution that has been accepted into the Software.

1.9  "You" (or "Your") means any natural person, legal person, corporation,
     partnership, joint venture, governmental body, educational institution, or
     any other entity exercising rights under this License.

1.10 "Distribution" means any act of making the Software or a Derivative Work
     available to any third party by any means, including but not limited to
     physical distribution of storage media, electronic transmission, making
     available for download, hosting as a service, providing access through a
     network, or any other means of conveyance.

1.11 "Network Use" means enabling any third party to interact with the Software
     or a Derivative Work over a computer network (including but not limited to
