4.4  CONTRIBUTION-BACK OBLIGATION.

     (a) If You create a Derivative Work that modifies, extends, improves, or
         fixes any component of the Software's core computational engine
         (including but not limited to: spectral basis implementations,
         decomposition algorithms, propagation routines, inverse reconstruction
         methods, convergence diagnostics, energy functionals, momentum
         observables, profile compression algorithms, or any mathematical or
         physical computation module), You must make a good-faith effort to
         submit those modifications as a Contribution to the Licensor's
         official repository within ninety (90) calendar days of the first
         Distribution or Network Use of the Derivative Work.

     (b) "Good-faith effort" means, at minimum:
         (i)   Opening a pull request or merge request to the official
               repository containing the modifications in a form suitable for
               review and integration;
         (ii)  Providing a clear description of the modifications and their
               purpose;
         (iii) Responding to reasonable review comments from the Licensor or
               other Contributors within thirty (30) calendar days.

     (c) The Licensor is under no obligation to accept any Contribution.  If
         the Licensor declines a Contribution, Your obligation under this
         Section is satisfied, provided You have made the good-faith effort
         described in subsection (b).

     (d) This Section does not require You to submit Contributions that consist
         solely of application-specific business logic, user interface code,
         configuration, or other components that are specific to Your particular
         use case and do not constitute improvements to the Software's core
         computational capabilities.

     (e) For the avoidance of doubt, this contribution-back obligation is in
         addition to, and does not replace, the Source Code availability
         obligation in Section 4.1.  Even if You submit a Contribution that is
         declined, You must still make the complete Source Code available as
         required by Section 4.1.

