================================================================================
                  ARTICLE 5 — ANTI-MISAPPROPRIATION PROVISIONS
================================================================================

5.1  PROHIBITION ON MISREPRESENTATION OF ORIGIN.

     (a) You may not represent, directly or by implication, that any Derivative
         Work is the original Software or is unrelated to the Software.

     (b) You may not remove, alter, or obscure any indication that a Derivative
         Work is derived from the Software.

     (c) If You create a Derivative Work that provides substantially similar
         functionality to the Software (including but not limited to spectral
         decomposition, modal analysis, wave-packet simulation, profile
         compression, or inverse reconstruction on bounded domains), You must
         include a clear and prominent statement in the Derivative Work's
         documentation, README, and any public description that the Derivative
         Work is derived from or based upon Spectral Packet Engine.

5.2  SUBSTANTIALLY SIMILAR WORKS.

     (a) If You independently develop a work that is substantially similar to
         the Software in structure, sequence, or organization, and You had
         access to the Software's Source Code prior to or during the
         development of such work, such work shall be presumed to be a
         Derivative Work under this License, and You bear the burden of proving
         by clear and convincing evidence that no copying occurred.

     (b) Evidence of substantial similarity includes but is not limited to:
         similar variable names, function names, class hierarchies, algorithm
         structures, code organization, file structures, API designs, error
         messages, comments, documentation patterns, and data structures.

     (c) This presumption is consistent with the "access plus substantial
         similarity" test applied by courts in the United States (Arnstein v.
         Porter, 154 F.2d 464, 2d Cir. 1946; Oracle Am., Inc. v. Google LLC,
         593 U.S. 1, 2021), the European Union (SAS Institute Inc v. World
         Programming Ltd, C-406/10, CJEU 2012), and Turkey (FSEK Articles 1
         and 2; Turkish Court of Cassation precedent on software originality).

5.3  TRADEMARK RESERVATION.

     (a) This License does not grant You any right to use the Project Name,
         any trademark, service mark, trade name, logo, or trade dress of the
         Licensor, except as necessary to comply with the attribution
         requirements of Section 4.3.

     (b) You must not use the Project Name or any confusingly similar name in
         the title, package name, module name, command name, or primary
         identifier of any Derivative Work without the Licensor's prior
         written consent.

     (c) You may describe Your Derivative Work as "based on Spectral Packet
         Engine" or "derived from Spectral Packet Engine" without additional
         permission, provided such description is accurate and does not imply
         endorsement by the Licensor.

